attributes.title: Objectification and Women's Sexual Satisfaction - Replication of Calogero & Thompson (2009)

q1.value: Self-Objectification and Women's Sexual Satisfaction: Replication of Calogero & Thompson (2009)

q3.value:
Self-objectification (operationalized as the body surveillance sub-scale of the Objectified Body Consciousness Scale) has been found to indirectly predict women's sexual satisfaction through appearance anxiety during sexual activity and similar constructs (Barzoki, Kontula, Mokhtariaraghi, & Mahboubishariatpanahi, 2017; Claudat & Warren, 2014; Robbins & Reissing, 2018; Vencill, Tebbe, & Garos, 2015). However, Calogero and Thompson (2009) found a direct relationship between body surveillance and sexual satisfaction. This may be due to the specific inclusion criteria they implemented that were unique to this study. We will be attempting to see if their results replicate in a higher power study, as well as testing new path analysis models of  the variables and reporting qualitative data from open-ended responses.

References:

Barzoki, M. H., Kontula, O., Mokhtariaraghi, H., & Mahboubishariatpanahi, N. (2017). Dual contradictory effects of self-objectification on sexual satisfaction. Sexuality & Culture, 21(2), 627–642. doi:10.1007/s12119-017-9408-z


Calogero, R. M., & Thompson, J. K. (2009). Potential implications of the objectification of women’s bodies for women’s sexual satisfaction. Body Image, 6(2), 145–148. doi:10.1016/j.bodyim.2009.01.001

Claudat, K., & Warren, C. S. (2014). Self-objectification, body self-consciousness during sexual activities, and sexual satisfaction in college women. Body Image, 11(4), 509–515. doi:10.1016/j.bodyim.2014.07.006

Robbins, A.-R., & Reissing, E. D. (2018). Out of “Objectification Limelight”? The contribution of body appreciation to sexual adjustment in midlife women. The Journal of Sex Research, 55(6), 758–771. doi:10.1080/00224499.2017.1372352

Vencill, J. A., Tebbe, E. A., & Garos, S. (2015). It’s not the size of the boat or the motion of the ocean: The role of self-objectification, appearance anxiety, and depression in female sexual functioning. Psychology of Women Quarterly, 39(4), 471–483. doi:10.1177/0361684315587703

q5.value: Observational Study - Data is collected from study subjects that are not randomly assigned to a treatment. This includes surveys, “natural experiments,” and regression discontinuity designs.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: Correlational, cross-sectional design, facilitated through an online survey.

q10.value: Registration prior to any human observation of the data

question.value: We will be recruiting participants from the pool of Research Experience Program (REP) students at the University of Minnesota, i.e., students who are enrolled in psychology courses at the University during the semester(s) of data collection. The study will be listed on the REP webpage, visible only to the REP pool, and students can read a short description and decide if they wish to participate. No recruiting efforts will be made aside from this. Participants will be compensated with 1 REP point, which goes toward receiving extra credit in their psychology courses. The inclusion criteria are that each participant must be eligible to participate in REP studies, and must identify as a woman. Data collection will occur during Fall semester 2019 (Sep.-Dec.)

q14.value:
Our expectation is a
moderate effect size, r = .20, which is typical of research on individual
differences. Taking into account statistical interactions and individual
differences, we require a sample size of at least 400 to have 80% and alpha
of .05.

q20.value: All of the predictor/outcome variables used in the regression are continuous and don’t require transformation. Data from the relationship status and relationship length variables, and the sexual experience and sexual history variables, will be recoded to be used for subgroup analyses (see indices section.)

q21.value: Standardized regression coefficients will be tested for significance at the alpha=0.05 level using z-statistics, with a value above 1.96 indicating significance at the .05 level.  Fit indices for each model will be calculated using the Chi-Squared Test of Goodness of Fit (with a value close to 0 and significance at level <.05 indicating good fit), Comparative Fit Index (with a value of 0.90 or greater indicating acceptable fit), and the Root Mean Square Error of Approximation (with a value of 0.06 or less indicating acceptable fit). Bayesian Information Criterion values will also be calculated for each model, with the model with the lowest value demonstrating the best fit. R2 and Adjusted R2 will be calculated to show us the percentage of variance not accounted for by each model. Each of the four models will be compared based on fit indices and R2 values.

q22.value: We will include two manipulation checks, and data from participants who fail both of them will not be included in analyses. We will also exclude data from participants who don’t report their sexual history, relationship status, height, & weight, and who fail to complete the media internalization measure. Outliers will not be excluded from the data, but as mentioned above, we will use bootstrapping analyses to acquire accurate standard errors.

q23.value: We will use Full Information Maximum Likelihood Estimation to provide population parameters and handle missing data.

question2a.value: The design will be a 2x2x3 design (CS type, between: geometric shape vs. meat) x (UCS-negative type, within: pathogen-relevant vs. pathogen-irrelevant) x (conditioning, within: CS+pos vs. CS+neg vs. no-CS).

question2b.value:
Participants will have an explicit and an implicit measure of ratings. These ratings will be used as the dependent variables. 
Explicit ratings: 
In each session, out of 12 stimuli, participants will rate 4 of the CS stimuli before conditioning and 8 of the CS stimuli after conditioning on "How much do you like this image?" (1=Strongly dislike, 7= Strongly like). 

Implicit ratings:
In each session participants will go through an Affect Misattribution Procedure in which they will rate if the Chinese characters they see after the 12 CS stimuli are pleasant or unpleasant than average.

question3b.value: As in Study 1 of this project, we will include participant sex as a factor in our analysis (see the uploaded document for details).

question10b.value: Please see the uploaded document "Preregistration_FoodConditioning_Study4" for the materials and procedure in detail.

question4b.value:
In the advertisement, only non-vegetarian participants will be asked to participate in the study. 
Participants who participated in an earlier lab study (https://osf.io/w7942) will not participate.

question5b.value: Study will be conducted in the psychology labs at Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam. Data will be collected from participants who are under 35 years old and who are not vegan or vegetarian.

question6b.value: We will stop data collection when there are 160 participants that participated in both sessions.

question7b.value: We will stop data collection when there are 160 participants that participated in both sessions.

question8b.value:
In the advertisement, only non-vegetarian participants will be asked to participate in the study. Participants will be asked if they are a vegetarian or vegan later in the study again. Participants who do not eat meat or who indicate speaking Chinese will be excluded from the analyses. These exclusions are planned because they might affect ratings of food images (if the participant is vegetarian or vegan), and ratings of the Chinese characters in the Affect Misattribution Procedure (if participant knows Chinese). Following suggestions in Payne & Lundberg (2014) we will also exclude participants who consistently press only one key throughout the Affect Misattribution Procedure task.


Payne, K., & Lundberg, K. (2014). The affect misattribution procedure: Ten years of evidence on reliability, validity, and mechanisms. Social and Personality Psychology Compass, 8, 672-686.

question1a.value:
1) Evaluations of meats and geometric shapes will vary depending on the images that CS’s are paired with during a conditioning task (i.e., there will be a main effect of pairing valence on evaluations). Means will be highest for images paired with positive images, and they will be lowest for images paired with negative images.

2) The effect described above will be moderated by UCS negative image type. Pairings with pathogen-relevant negative images will result in stronger evaluative conditioning effects for meats compared to abstract geometric shapes. The effect of pairings with pathogen-irrelevant negative images will not vary across meats versus shapes, nor will the effects of pairings with positive or neutral images.

question1c.value:
For the study we will use a mixed model approach. 


We will recode conditioning data (CS+neg, CS+pos, no-CS) to obtain two dummy coded variables with the reference category being CS+neg
CS+neg                        0         0      
CS+pos                        1         0      
No-CS                          0         1       

With these dummy coded variables we will examine the difference between, 1) CS+pos, and CS+neg and 2) no-CS and CS+neg and through these two we can retrieve information on the difference between 3) CS+pos and no-CS  on explicit and implicit ratings. 

We will test the fixed effects of the two dummy coded variables, UCS-negative type (pathogen-relevant versus pathogen irrelevant), CS type (geometric shapes versus meats), and interactions between these variables. We will also control for session order.  Participant sex will be included into our analysis model as women are more disgust sensitive than men (Sparks et al., 2018), and they eat less meat than men (Beardsworth & Bryman, 1999; Fessler, Arguello, Mekdara, & Macias, 2003). We will model fixed effects of participant sex and the interaction between participant sex and CS type. 

Random intercepts will be modeled for participants and CS images. We will also model random slopes that improve model fit and do not lead to non-converging models.
Our key prediction concerns the interaction between conditioning, CS-type, and UCS-negative type.  We predict an interaction between CS-type UCS-negative type for both dummy coded variables.  

For meats, we expect a simple effect of UCS-negative type, with pathogen-relevant cues leading to stronger conditioning than pathogen-irrelevant cues. For geometric shapes, we expect no difference in the effectiveness of pathogen-relevant versus pathogen-irrelevant conditioning. 
Any changes with the analysis plan will be justified and updated.


Mentioned references:
Beardsworth, A., & Bryman, A. (1999). Meat consumption and vegetarianism among young adults in the UK. British Food Journal, 101, 289–300

Sparks, A. M., Fessler, D. M., Chan, K. Q., Ashokkumar, A., & Holbrook, C. (2018). Disgust as a mechanism for decision making under risk: illuminating sex differences and individual risk-taking correlates of disgust propensity. Emotion (in press).

question2c.value: We will analyze the data using multi-level modeling.

attributes.title: Somatosensory aspects of mandibular motor control in adults who do and do not stutter
attributes.description:
A broad range of physiological and behavioral research has demonstrated that people who stutter (PWS) have deficits in the ability to process auditory feedback and utilize it in the regulation of speech motor control. Atypical features of central neurophysiology include diminished grey matter development and integrity of white matter tracts between key auditory processing and premotor areas involved in speech planning and production (Beal 2015; Kell et al. 2009; Chang et al. 2008; Watkins et al. 2008; Chang et al. 2018; Neef et al. 2015). Characteristic modulation of auditory cortical activity immediately prior to speech production is also absent in PWS (Daliri & Max 2015a, 2015b; Daliri & Max 2018), which may reflect inefficient priming of sensory cortices necessary to detect unexpected feedback errors in the upcoming utterance (Eliades & Wang 2008; Eliades & Tsunada 2018). Indeed, there is a wide range of evidence showing that PWS have reduced adaptive speech responses to predictable auditory feedback perturbations (Daliri et al. 2018 [adults only]; Daliri & Max 2018), as well as diminished online responses to unexpected single-trial perturbations (Cai et al. 2012; Loucks et al. 2012). Thus, the dysregulated cortical network connectivity in PWS appears to manifest as a specific deficit in auditory feedback processing for the regulation of ongoing speech motor control.
Conversely, less is known about the ability of PWS to process somatosensory feedback in the regulation of orofacial movement control. In people who do not stutter (PWNS), the role of somatosensation has been demonstrated through jaw and orofacial kinematic responses to both predictable (Nasir & Ostry 2006; Tremblay et al. 2003; 2008; Lametti et al. 2012; Feng et al. 2011) and unexpected online (Abbs & Gracco 1984, Folins & Abbs 1975; Tiede et al. 2006) physical perturbations to the articulators during speech and non-speech movements. However, the profile of these responses in PWS is unknown. Clearly there are structural abnormalities in the neural connections between auditory processing and speech motor cortical areas in PWS, but there are also specific abnormalities within (pre-)motor areas which may limit integration of other sensory signals for speech motor control too (for reviews see Neef 2015; Chang 2018). Given that PWS also show atypical movement characteristics during basic non-speech movement control (Daliri, Propenko, Flanagan & Max 2015; Forster & Webster 2001; Max, Caruso & Gracco 2003), it may be that they experience generalized sensory processing difficulties which affect multiple sensory domains and effector systems. Alternatively, it could be that somatic sensorimotor processing is relatively intact for PWS and that stuttering arises from problems specific to auditory-motor integration or a conflict between somatosensory and auditory processing during speech motor control.
As such, this project broadly aims to investigate how PWS differ from neurotypical controls in their ability to integrate somatosensory feedback in the regulation of mandibular speech and non-speech movement control.

name.value: Non-speech mandibular motor control and online compensation for unexpected force perturbations in adults who stutter.

other.value:
To examine the kinematic profile of movements, additional linear mixed effects models (same design as outlined above) will be performed on movement duration, peak opening velocity and number of sub-movements during opening (number of velocity peaks) for each trial.
To examine any potential learning effects on performance resulting from the accuracy feedback condition, we will also take absolute target error across all trials for this condition (split by trial type) and fit with additional regression models.

sample.value: There will be two groups of participants; (1) at least 12 adults who do not stutter and (2) the same number of age-, hand- and sex-matched adults who do stutter – these groups will be the same as those who participated in another preregistered experiment (title “Speech motor adaptation to mandibular force-field perturbations in adults who stutter”) which will be performed immediately before this one.

outliers.value: Data from incomplete experimental protocols or other extenuating circumstances (misunderstanding of instructions, technical or measurement errors) will not be included in final analysis, but the number of such cases will be disclosed as necessary. Trials in which participants do not cross the force-threshold boundary twice (i.e. once for opening and once for closing) will be excluded from analysis, the exact proportion of trials excluded on this basis will be detailed as necessary.

conditions.value: Both groups of participants (adults who stutter and adults who do not stutter) will perform all conditions which includes all of the up, down and no force trials as well as the accuracy feedback and no accuracy feedback conditions (see above for details).

hypothesis.value: Do adults who stutter differ from those who do not in their ability to perform target-based, non-speech mandibular movements in the presence and absence of unexpected loads.
